        correct: 1,
        explanation: "Option B is correct: falling train loss with flat or rising eval loss is the textbook overfitting signature — the model is fitting training-set noise instead of the generalizable target behavior. The response is to stop early, clean and dedup the data, reduce epochs, and check for train-eval leakage that could also be distorting the picture. Option A deepens the exact problem — chasing training loss to zero increases overfitting. Option C is backwards — the eval set is doing its job by catching the divergence; discarding it removes the only honest signal available. Option D doesn't address the cause — a higher learning rate doesn't fix overfitting to noise and typically destabilizes training further; the issue is data quality and run length, not step size.",
