        explanation: "Option B is correct: the symptom is the classic alignment tax — over-optimizing toward 'safe/preferred' produces an over-refusing, hedging model. The evaluation fix is to measure both directions, helpfulness on valid requests and correct refusal on bad ones, since a one-sided refusal metric is trivially gamed by a model that refuses everything. Option A is exactly the trap — a perfect refusal score alongside collapsed helpfulness is a failure, not a success. Option C misattributes the cause — over-refusal here comes from over-aggressive tuning and pair imbalance, not reward-model weakness, so strengthening it in the same direction won't restore helpfulness. Option D would make it worse — a larger penalty toward the already over-refusing behavior deepens the over-refusal instead of rebalancing it.",
