    takeaway: "Productized fine-tuning is eval-driven or it's guesswork. Build the held-out, production-representative eval *first* — it's the contract for whether a tune helped. Because narrow tuning causes catastrophic forgetting, always evaluate two suites (new-task *and* regression) and gate the ship on both: a tune that wins the task but regresses elsewhere never ships. Run the flywheel — prod failures → curate → tune → eval gate → A/B → ship → collect — and respect the measurement pitfalls: LLM-as-judge biases (randomize/rubric/spot-check) and Goodhart's law (rotating/blind evals; trust the A/B when it diverges from a rising offline score). Govern it like a product with dataset/version lineage, reproducibility, and instant adapter rollback, so a regression is caught by a gate and reverted in minutes — not discovered by a customer three weeks later.",
    scenario: "Now let's put this to work. You shipped a fine-tune that clearly improved the target task — billing-question answers got noticeably better in your demos. Three weeks later, support notices the model now botches *refund* questions it used to handle perfectly.\n\nTake a moment: what failed, and what would have prevented it? Here's the reasoning, step by step. The failure is **catastrophic forgetting** — tuning on the narrow billing task moved weights in ways that degraded the previously-working refund capability. And it shipped *silently* for one reason: you measured only the new task and never checked whether the tune broke old capabilities. The structural fix is exactly the discipline we built: always evaluate on *two* suites before shipping — the new-task eval (did the tune help?) AND a regression suite of previously-working capabilities (did the tune break anything?) — and gate the ship on *both* conditions. A tune that wins the task but regresses elsewhere never ships. Then, because adapters are tiny artifacts, a regression caught by that gate — or later by a production A/B — triggers an *instant* rollback by re-pointing the router at the previous adapter, no 140GB redeploy. That's the whole point of the eval-driven loop: a regression is caught by a gate and reverted in minutes, not discovered by a customer three weeks later. That difference is what separates a fine-tuning hobby from a fine-tuning product.",
